XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Ashlee Vance [ https://substack.com/redirect/5ac032c3-d73a-4ada-9f51-69c29a=
e1adfc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 for Bloomberg
Exactly why Brin wants a fleet of airships remains a partial mystery. He ha=
s declined many interview requests to discuss LTA. Still, over the past cou=
ple of years, Weston has let me observe the construction of Pathfinder 1 an=
d the early stages of its successors, and Brin=E2=80=99s rationale seems st=
raightforward enough: He just likes airships.
One of the benefits of having billionaires is that they can build things fo=
r humanity just because they like them, without worrying about returns. Exa=
mple 1a) Sergey Brin and airships. By some estimations, Brin has already in=
vested over $250M into his airship company LTA and, from what I can tell, t=
here=E2=80=99s really no end in sight on the cost front and no major plan t=
o start monetizing in a meaningful way. Brin, worth north of a $100B, just =
likes airships=E2=80=A6so humanity gets airships.
There are a few examples of this already =E2=80=94 the most obvious one=E2=
=80=99s being Musk & SpaceX (although more returns focused) and Bezos & Blu=
e Origin (less returns focused). Longevity is another current cause c=C3=A9=
l=C3=A8bre. If you have other examples of billionaires that have turned exp=
ensive hobbies into companies/industries that have had a big impact on soci=
ety, let us know in the comments.
We think we=E2=80=99ll see a lot more of this in the coming years. A lot of=
 nerds who grew up reading sci-fi have made a lot of money selling software=
 over the past couple of decades, and we suspect they=E2=80=99ll put those =
profits to bring sci-fi to life, sometimes for returns and sometimes becaus=
e they just like airships.=20
(3) An Interesting Thread on Renewable Energy Cost Curves [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/b4a0c27a-1b07-43c5-8303-924e16ba9126?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Link to thread [ https://substack.com/redirect/b4a0c27a-1b07-43c5-8303-924e=
16ba9126?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] from @JohnArnoldFndtn [ https://substack.com/redirect/5780c149-77b8-4f69=
-8646-5819cd88a1f2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ]
The gist of John Arnold=E2=80=99s thread is that the cost of solar and wind=
 energy have actually increased in the last couple of years. At Not Boring,=
 we often talk about renewables=E2=80=99 learning curves and major cost dec=
reases, so we were interested when this thread popped up noting that costs =
are actually going up. Even still, there=E2=80=99s good news.
The factors driving up costs are less technological than they are macroecon=
omic or bureaucratic. The major drivers are interest rates, tariffs, permit=
ting, labor costs, etc. All very real (and frustrating) cost drivers, but a=
lso all cyclical and/or solvable. Over a long enough time horizon, our best=
 bet is that these spikes will be indiscernible on renewable=E2=80=99s smoo=
thing, decreasing cost curve.=20
(4) 10 Thoughts From the Fourth Trimester [ https://substack.com/redirect/9=
dbe55a6-b8d3-495c-a2a0-158ee1101bab?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Tim Urban [ https://substack.com/redirect/02291e71-1a91-4e4c-89b5-10f6cf556=
70c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] fo=
r Wait Buy Why
10) Having a baby really makes you think about the future: Every parent in =
history has brought their baby into a world with an uncertain future. But o=
ur future is the uncertainest. My baby might live a life a lot like mine, j=
ust a little more futuristic. Or she might live to 500. She might live most=
 of her life with a brain-machine interface [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/002facca-b1e0-4896-848c-be985d428006?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] implanted in her head, thinking with her ow=
n superintelligent AI. She might suffer through civilizational collapse. Sh=
e might live in a world that would seem like utopia to us today. She might =
live on Mars. She might meet aliens. She might die in the apocalypse. There=
=E2=80=99s just no way to know. It makes all of those fun, exciting, terrif=
ying conversations about the future hit just a little harder.
Tim Urban=E2=80=99s superpower is breaking down life=E2=80=99s most complex=
 topics =E2=80=94 time, relationships, careers =E2=80=94 into understandabl=
e, bite-sized truth nuggets. He wielded that superpower in his most recent =
essay, a reflection on what it=E2=80=99s like to be the parent of a newborn=
 baby.
I am not a father. I hope to be in the not-so-distant future. And Tim=E2=80=
=99s first 9 observations may help me more smoothly navigate those first 3 =
months when the time comes. But observation #10 really struck me: having a =
baby really makes you think about the future.=20
(Packy here: that is 100% true and you can see it in the things we write ab=
out in Not Boring.)
Humans have no idea what the world of their children will look like. Some h=
umans envision the worst case scenario. Others envision a futuristic utopia=
=2E But the truth is, we=E2=80=99re really=
 bad at predicting the future on a=20=
macro scale, let alone predicting the micro-experiences of an individual. A=
nd that=E2=80=99s kind of the point. That uncertainty seems to be what make=
s parenting so hard, yet so exhilarating. How do you prepare your kid for a=
 future you know nothing about?
There=E2=80=99s no right answer. But we humans will keep on making babies a=
nd trying to figure it out! Tim Urban FTW, per usual.=20
(5) A Crypto Future [ https://substack.com/redirect/e5797b04-4110-45d5-b6b7=
-cef40463c782?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ]
0xsmac  & Compound Crypto
Crypto-enabled tools and their privacy protection guarantees are showing re=
al promise =E2=80=93 first for rare disease data collection aggregation, wh=
ich has led to meaningful scientific breakthroughs that weren=E2=80=99t exp=
ected so quickly.
A mid-sized city (100k-500k people) in North Texas proposes a complete ener=
gy independent infrastructure powered by an emerging crypto network.
Packy again. One of the things I admire most about Compound [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/db1f197d-94ec-4d82-b634-cff9ca50c4a3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is that they write about an=
d invest in wild, futuristic things in a balanced and hype-free way. Counte=
r to the =E2=80=9Ccrypto to AI=E2=80=9D meme, they=E2=80=99ve been investin=
g in crypto and AI since before both were cool, and are as quick to point o=
ut the risks and bubbles as they are the upsides.=20
All that setup to say that I loved reading their measured but optimistic ta=
ke on the evolution of crypto over the next few years. The piece is in the =
Tell Good Stories [ https://substack.com/redirect/30aebf54-9c84-4f24-90ea-4=
4b7715db931?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] genre, writing about the future as if it=E2=80=99s happening in real-=
time, and full of very specific predictions, good, bad, and neutral. I foun=
d myself alternating between nodding and shaking my head, a good indicator =
of the piece=E2=80=99s balance.=20
Despite the bear market and the very real headwinds, there are a ton of tai=
lwinds for crypto, too. I particularly appreciate the intersections they hi=
ghlight with DeSci [ https://substack.com/redirect/dc03cfa7-4c08-498f-a48e-=
58b718d3892c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ], energy, VR/AR, and AI. When we look back in a decade, I believe the=
 biggest impacts are going to come from products that take advantage of a b=
unch of different technologies to create delightful experiences and solve b=
ig challenges.=20
A good reminder as we head into the long weekend to zoom out.=20
Bonus: Succession Series Finale [ https://substack.com/redirect/8c3b530b-9c=
c2-4da5-b533-9ba50df3e680?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
If you read Not Boring, chances are you also watch Succession. The Shakespe=
arean spoof of media mogulism comes to an end this Sunday night. The show, =
which was relatively under the radar for the first 1 or 2 seasons, is now c=
onsidered, by many, to be among the greatest television series of all time.=
 We tend to agree. Hell, I actually enjoyed watching what was basically a l=
ivestream of a funeral last week.
We=E2=80=99ll save you our predictions =E2=80=94 you=E2=80=99ve probably be=
en bombarded with them elsewhere =E2=80=94 and just leave you with this, on=
e last time:
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tu=
esday. Enjoy the long weekend.
Thanks for reading,
Dan

